        <h2> Diet for 
soccer player: </h2> <br />

        <h3> Diet for footballers in preseason </h3>

        <p> The preseason usually lasts from 1 month to 3 months, in this period the priority is to reduce the percentage of body fat and train endurance and muscular strength. 
        A diet planned for months can highlight the genetic potential of the player, provided it is planned according to the energy requirements of training.
           The diet for soccer players must be adjusted in carbohydrates and unsaturated fats to supply the necessary energy.
            <br />
             <br />
           Protein diets to enhance lean mass are not recommended, but balanced protein consumption at all meals and
           snacks, taking into account training sessions. </p>

        <h3> Diet during the season </h3>

        <p> You should consume enough carbohydrates and electrolytes before, during and after games / workouts to boost performance and endurance. 
        Try to eat 5 meals a day. Eat low-glycemic carbohydrates such as oatmeal, brown rice, quinoa, whole wheat pasta, artisan bread, to
           maximize your performance. Include lean protein and favorable fat at every meal, based on the plate rule. 
            <br />
             <br />
        Consume fried and fat in your diet for footballers in moderation, as they are slowly digested and can create a feeling of heaviness or indigestion during the game.
           Foods high in fiber can cause gas or gastrointestinal upset during the intense action of a soccer game. </p>

        <h3> What to do on match day? </h3>

        <p> On match day you should eat 2-3 hours before and drink enough fluids to balance satiety, delay fatigue and avoid cramps during the match
            90 minutes, or longer in case of extension.
            <br />
             <br />
            Footballers consume a lot of muscle glycogen during matches, in addition there is a great loss of fluids due to sweating, it is interesting that
            take a few sips of your sports drink, at half-time or if you approach the bench, to replace these losses. </p>

        <h3> What to eat after a game? </h3> <br />

        <p> For a fast and effective recovery you must recharge the glycogen stores,
            promote muscle growth and repair, and rehydrate you. 

       The first 60 minutes are very important for muscle recovery since
            This is when the highest assimilation of nutrients is achieved.
            The recovery diet depends on individual physical goals: 

        - If the goal is to increase muscle strength and size,
            choose foods with high caloric density as a sandwich
            <strong> (cheese, ham, tuna, chicken, egg) </strong>, fruit salad with yogurt, semi-rice pudding,
            cereal bars <strong> (it is preferable that they also provide protein) </strong>
            or liquid recovery supplements. 

        -If the goal is to reduce weight and body fat percentage,
            Your Sports Nutritionist should adjust the basketball diet with calorie restriction criteria.
            An example of a post-training or competition snack would be a piece of seasonal fruit,
            2 slices of lean cold cuts and 2 walnuts.
            Consult the infographic for other snack options for athletes. </p>

    
         <h3> Importance of hydration in football </h3>

       <p>Hydration is very important, during intense sports practice changes in body weight usually occur, mainly caused by
            loss of water in the form of sweat and breathing. 

         The two hours before the game you must drink fluids to compensate for any subsequent losses. It is also important to drink during the match
            Form distributed every 20-30 min a sports drink to also replace the salts lost with sweat. </p>

